				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\approx$$\end{document} 50 × 50 × 50 cm3 and requires 7 W power (usually from standard lead or lithium based batteries).

To achieve a good spatial resolution imaging of the geological object, even far away from the detectors, a fine angular resolution (better than 1 degree) is required for the measurements. Imaging requires angular classification (binning) of the data for muon counts and efficiencies. Position resolution of a single CCC layer is \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\approx$$\end{document} 1.5 mm, resulting in better than 5 mrad (0.3 degrees) nominal angular resolution for the muon tracks. Practical angular binning is usually around 1 degree.

